<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1163749-how-extensive-should-one-s-knowledge-about">How extensive should one&#39;s knowledge about Freud&#39;s ideas be, in order to properly enjoy the content of this book?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1163749'><a id="like_count_community_question_1163749" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/1163749?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">3 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F357636.Civilization_and_Its_Discontents">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1163749-how-extensive-should-one-s-knowledge-about">4 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1163749-how-extensive-should-one-s-knowledge-about">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/42139171-marcelo-galuppo"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1609689374i/42139171._UY100_CR24,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/42139171-marcelo-galuppo">Marcelo Galuppo</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Freud is a great writer, a very clear scholar. Most of his books, although intended for the scholar, can be understood by anyone. This one is speciall<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Freud is a great writer, a very clear scholar. Most of his books, although intended for the scholar, can be understood by anyone. This one is specially an easy one (besides part VI, when he discussed narcisismus). You could profit of reading "Introduction to Narcisismus" before you read this one, but it is not necessary.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
